article.headline: Michigan 75, Ohio State 64
article.story: ANN ARBOR, Mich. (AP) -- Lester Abram may not make dazzling shots or spectacular dunks. But he sure is effective. Michigan's leading scorer had 20 points and six rebounds to lead Michigan to a 75-64 win against Ohio State on Sunday. "He doesn't do a lot of flashy things. He just knocks down his shots," said teammate Bernard Robinson, who had 13 points and five assists. Abram made six of eight shots, four of five 3-pointers, and all four of his free throws. "I just pick and choose my times to shoot," the sophomore guard said. "I try not to force things. "I had a good offensive game, but I had too many turnovers, so I don't think I played well overall." The Wolverines (16-9, 7-7 Big Ten) have won three of four, but need to finish strong on the road against Indiana and Northwestern and in the conference tournament to play in the NCAA tournament for the first time since 1998. The last time Michigan played in the postseason was four years ago when it lost to Notre Dame in the first round of the NIT. "I really don't want to play in the NIT," Abram said. "I think we'll be in pretty good shape if we win these last two and play well in the Big Ten tournament." Abram scored 10 points in the first half to help Michigan earn a nine-point lead and had 10 points after halftime as the Wolverines stayed ahead comfortably. Tony Stockman scored 22 points for the Buckeyes (13-14, 5-9), who had won two straight, both on the road. Terence Dials scored 13 and Velimir Radinovic added 11 points and seven rebounds. "I think the big difference was our inability to guard them and stop them when we needed to," Ohio State coach Jim O'Brien said. "They scored in transition and (on) offensive putbacks. That was a big dilemma for us." Abram made two 3-pointers and a putback in two-plus minutes to give Michigan a 52-38 lead midway through the second half. Ohio State pulled within seven, but could not get closer. "(Michigan) may be the most talented and athletic team in the conference," O'Brien said. "We are not those things, and that hurt us." While it may be difficult for the Wolverines to make the NCAA tournament, it was impossible just a few months before the season. The NCAA accepted the school's many self-imposed sanctions -- stemming from its involvement with now-deceased booster Ed Martin -- but added an additional year of a postseason ban. In September, however, Michigan became the first school in five years to win an appeal of a postseason ban and is now eligible to play in the NCAA or NIT this season.
